Month = {JUN},
Abstract = {Mussels (Mytilus galloprovincialis Lamarck) were exposed to the toxic
   cyanobacterium Microcystis aeruginosa Kutz. emend Elkin for 16 days in
   order to study bioaccumulation of the cyclic heptapeptide toxin
   microcystin-LR. After this time period the animals were fed marine
   phytoplankton for 2 weeks and the amount of microcystin in the mussels
   was monitored again. During the exposure phase mussels attained a
   maximum of 10.5 mu g of toxin per g dry mussel weight at day 10.
   Microcystin was detectable after the second day of exposure. The
   percentage of toxin that was taken up relative to the total amount
   administered varied from 24.1\% to 54.8\%. When the mussels were fed
   marine phytoplankton there was a 50\% decrease in the amount of
   detectable toxin in the mussels within 2 days. This was followed by a
   slight increase in toxin levels over 5 days with no microcystin-LR being
   detected at day 13. The major part of the toxin (96\%) was found in the
   digestive gland + stomach while the gills, muscle, foot, and other
   organs combined had less than 4\% of the total toxin. The results
   presented here show that cyanobacteria blooms present in estuaries where
   bivalves are growing naturally constitute a health hazard in that these
   organisms can retain microcystins and transfer them through the food
   chain.},
