Pages = {167-175},
Month = {APR},
Abstract = {Contamination of bivalves with yessotoxins (YTXs) has been reported
   since 1987 in several coastal environments. In our study we investigated
   the accumulation and the metabolism of YTXs in 2 bivalve species
   important to German fisheries and aquaculture. Mussels and oysters.
   Mytilus edulis and Crassostrea gigas, were exposed to the YTX-producing
   dinoflagellate Protoceratium reticulatum isolated from the North Sea.
   Toxin profiles from algae and bivalves were analyzed by liquid
   chromatography with tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS). It was evident
   that 45-hydroxy YTX (45-OH YTX), carboxy YTX (COOH YTX), and the
   putative 45-hydroxy-carboxy YTX (45-OH-COOH YTX) were the dominant YTX
   analogues in M. edulis. The oyster C. gigas displayed a different toxin
   profile. YTX, 45-OH YTX, and 45-OH-COOH YTX were also present, but COOH
   YTX was not detectable. Furthermore, 2 unidentified analogues with the
   same MS/MS transition ({[}M-H](-) > {[}M-H-SO3](-)) occurred in both
   bivalve species. Homo YTX and 45-hydroxy-homo YTX, which are regulated
   together with YTX and 45-OH YTX in 2002/225 EC were not detected. In
   general, we confirmed former field investigations on accumulation and
   metabolism of YTXs in M. edulis; however, this is the first study on
   accumulation and metabolism of YTXs in the oyster C. gigas.},
